        // ── Overview (Article) ───────────────────────────────────────────
        await GetOrCreateModule(new TrainingModule
        {
            Title = "Planning Cycles Overview",
            Slug = "planning-overview",
            Summary = "What planning cycles are, the two-week cadence, Day 1 planning flow, daily Top 3, and end-of-cycle rollover.",
            ContentType = TrainingContentType.Article,
            EstimatedMinutes = 5,
            IsPublished = true,
            SortOrder = 1,
            AppRoutes = """["/planning"]""",
            Tags = """["planning","cycles","backlog"]""",
            ContentJson = """{"body":"## Planning Cycles Overview\n\nPlanning Cycles bring structure to your shop's workflow by organizing backlog jobs into focused, time-boxed sprints. Instead of an ever-growing list of work, you commit a manageable set of jobs to a cycle, track progress, and review results at the end.\n\n### What Is a Planning Cycle?\n\nA planning cycle is a fixed-duration window — typically two weeks (14 days) — during which your team commits to completing a specific set of jobs. Each cycle has:\n- A **name** (e.g., 'Sprint 12' or 'Week of Mar 11')\n- A **start date** and **end date**\n- Optional **goals** describing what the team aims to accomplish\n- A **status** that progresses through the lifecycle: Planning → Active → Completed\n\n### The Two-Week Cadence\n\nThe default cycle length is 14 days, but you can set any duration when creating a cycle. The system calculates duration automatically from your start and end dates. Most shops find two-week cycles hit the sweet spot — long enough to make meaningful progress, short enough to course-correct quickly.\n\n### Day 1: Planning Day\n\nThe first day of each cycle is Planning Day. This is when you:\n1. **Review the backlog** — the left panel shows all uncommitted jobs from the backlog, filterable by search and priority\n2. **Commit jobs** — drag jobs from the backlog panel on the left into the cycle panel on the right, or click the + button on each backlog job\n3. **Set goals** — describe what the team aims to accomplish this cycle\n4. **Prioritize** — reorder committed entries by dragging them up or down in the cycle panel\n5. **Kick off the work** — the team starts on the committed jobs once everyone is aligned on the plan\n\n> **Planning vs. Active — what to expect.** A new cycle opens in **Planning** status, and you can run the whole cycle from there. Add jobs, reorder them, mark them done, and complete or roll the cycle over at the end — all of it works in Planning. Marking a cycle **Active** adds one thing: a days-remaining countdown on the board. So a Planning cycle is not a half-finished cycle waiting on a switch — it's a working cycle. Plan in it, commit to it, and track it the same way.\n\n### Who Can Do What (Roles)\n\nAnyone on the team can watch a cycle — Admins, Managers, PMs, Engineers, and Production Workers can all open the planning page and read the cycles, the backlog, and progress. **Making changes**, though, is limited to **Managers and Admins**: creating or editing a cycle, activating it, completing or rolling it over, adding a job, removing a job, reordering jobs, and marking a job done all take a Manager or Admin. Anyone else who tries one of those actions is turned away. Think of planning as a manager-run activity the whole team can follow. (Planning also has to be turned on for your site — when it's off, the page is hidden entirely.)\n\n### The Split-Panel Layout\n\nThe planning page splits into two sides:\n- **Left side (Backlog):** Lists every job not yet added to the current cycle. Search by job number or title, or narrow by priority. Jobs already in the selected cycle drop off the list.\n- **Right side (Cycle Board):** Shows the selected cycle's details — its name, date range, goals, progress bar, and the list of added jobs with whether each is done.\n\nDrag a job from the left and drop it on the right to add it. The backlog updates right away to hide the job you just added.\n\n### Daily Top 3\n\nEach evening, the app asks each team member to name their top 3 priorities for the next day. It's a quick daily check-in that keeps focus sharp without a full standup meeting. Your Top 3 is saved as a private, personal end-of-day note just for you — it's a reminder for yourself, not shared with the team and not posted to the cycle board.\n\n### Tracking Progress\n\nOnce a cycle is active, you track progress right on the cycle board:\n- **Mark jobs done** — click the circle on any job to mark it complete\n- **Progress bar** — shows how much is done (for example, '5 / 12' and '42%')\n- **Days remaining** — shows while the cycle is active, counting down to the end date\n- **Rolled-over mark** — jobs carried over from an earlier cycle show a small replay icon so you can spot the carryover work\n\n### End-of-Cycle: Completion and Rollover\n\nWhen the cycle ends, you have two options:\n\n1. **Complete & Roll Over** — marks the cycle Completed and starts a new cycle for you. Any unfinished jobs carry over to the new cycle with the 'rolled over' mark. The new cycle starts the day after the old one ends and keeps the same length.\n\n2. **Complete (No Rollover)** — marks the cycle Completed. Unfinished jobs go back to the backlog. No new cycle is created.\n\nBoth options ask you to confirm first, so you can't finish a cycle by accident.\n\n### Cycle Statuses\n\n| Status | Meaning |\n|--------|--------|\n| **Planning** | The status every new cycle starts in — and a fully working state. You can add, remove, reorder, and complete jobs freely, and you can complete or roll the cycle over right from here. |\n| **Active** | The cycle is underway. You can still add or remove jobs, the team is working, and the board shows a days-remaining countdown. The Complete & Roll Over and Complete buttons appear for Active cycles. |\n| **Completed** | The cycle is finished and read-only. Every job shows its final done-or-not state. |\n\n### When to Use Planning Cycles\n\n- When your backlog has more work than your team can tackle at once\n- When you want to create focus and commitment around a set of deliverables\n- When you need visibility into what was planned vs. what was actually completed\n- When you want to track how much work rolls over between cycles (a signal of over-commitment)","sections":[]}"""
        });

