            ContentJson = """{"body":"## When Planning Is Available, and Reading the Empty States\n\nPlanning Cycles are a feature your shop turns on. If planning isn't part of your setup, the page and its sidebar link simply aren't there — so if a coworker can't find planning at all, it hasn't been enabled for your shop, not that something is broken. Your home screen's cycle-progress card behaves the same way: with no planning in play, it just sits quiet rather than showing an error.\n\nThat's different from the empty states you'll see day to day once planning is on but you haven't built anything yet. Learn to read them so you know whether to create, commit, or keep going:\n- **\"No cycle selected\"** with a **Create first cycle** button — you haven't started a cycle. This is your Day 1 starting point.\n- **\"No jobs committed\"** — the cycle exists but is empty. Pull jobs over from the backlog to fill it.\n- **\"No available jobs\"** — the backlog has nothing left to commit (or your search and priority filters have hidden everything). Clear the filters to be sure before you conclude the backlog is truly empty.\n\nNone of these mean anything is wrong — they're just telling you where you are in building out the cycle.\n\n## Who Runs a Cycle vs. Who Follows It\n\nPlanning is a manager-run activity that the whole shop can follow. That split is worth understanding as a planner, because it shapes how you use the page with your team.\n\n**Everyone can watch.** Admins, Managers, PMs, Engineers, and Production Workers can all open planning and read the current cycle — its jobs, the progress bar, the days remaining, and what's rolled over. Point your team at the page so they can see the plan without asking you for a status update.\n\n**Managers and Admins make the changes.** Creating or editing a cycle, adding or removing a job, reordering, marking a job done, and completing or rolling over the cycle are all planner actions reserved for Managers and Admins. If a PM, Engineer, or floor worker tries to commit or complete a job, the app won't let the change through — the cycle they're seeing is a read-only view for them.\n\nSo treat the plan as yours to shape and the team's to watch: you drive the commitments and the reorder decisions; they get a live, shared picture of what the shop is working on this cycle.\n\n## The Date and Length Rules to Plan Around\n\nA few rules govern how a cycle's dates and length behave. Knowing them keeps your planning smooth:\n\n- **Name** is required — give the cycle something the team will recognize on the picker, like 'Sprint 12' or 'Week of Mar 11'. You have up to 100 characters.\n- **Start date and end date** are both required, and the end has to come after the start — a one-day cycle isn't allowed. If you set an end that isn't past the start, the cycle won't save and the form tells you to fix the date.\n- **Length is figured for you** from those two dates; you don't type a duration. This matters at rollover: when you roll a cycle over, the next one keeps the same length automatically, so a two-week cadence stays two weeks without you re-entering anything.\n- **Goals** are optional — a short paragraph on what the team is aiming for this cycle. Fill them in when the cycle has a real theme; skip them for routine weeks.\n\nOne thing to expect: every new cycle starts in Planning, and you can't set a different status when you create it. Editing later changes only the name, dates, and goals — never the status. The status moves on its own as you work and complete the cycle.\n\n## Which Cycle Shows On Your Home Screen\n\nYour home screen shows a cycle-progress card, and it's worth knowing which cycle lands there so it matches what you expect. The card follows your most recently started cycle — whichever un-finished cycle has the latest start date. Both Planning and Active cycles are eligible, so a brand-new cycle you're still planning can be the one on your home screen.\n\nTwo practical takeaways for a planner:\n- **Spin up next cycle's plan early and it takes over the card.** If you create a cycle with a later start date while an older one is still running, the newer one becomes the featured cycle right away. That's usually what you want during planning-day overlap, but be aware the card has moved on to the new plan.\n- **The card flags an overdue cycle.** If the end date has passed and work is still open, the card calls the cycle out as overdue — a nudge to complete it or roll it over so the next cycle can take the spotlight.\n","sections":[]}"""
        });

        Log.Information("Seeded Planning Cycles training modules");
    }
}
